04749nam a22006255i 9780822385875DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20042004ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1229161086  a97808223858757 a10.1515/97808223858752doi  a(DE-B1597)553934  a(OCoLC)1153045106  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aLIT0080002bisacsh04a895.6/099287/09021 aYoda, Tomiko, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGender and National Literature :bHeian Texts in the Constructions of Japanese Modernity /cTomiko Yoda; ed. by Masao Miyoshi, Harry Harootunian, Rey Chow. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2004] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b2 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAsia-Pacific: Culture, Politics, and Society : 4400tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote to the Reader -- tIntroduction -- t1.The Feminization of Heian and Eighteenth-Century Poetics -- t2. Gender and the Nationalization of Literature -- t3. Women and the Emergence of Heian Kana Writing -- t4. Politics and Poetics in The Tale of Genji -- t5. Tokieda’s Imperial Subject and the Textual Turn in Heian Literary Studies -- t6. Gender and Heian Narrative Form -- tEpilogue: Heian Texts and Feminist Subjects -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBoldly challenging traditional understandings of Heian literature, Tomiko Yoda reveals the connections between gender, nationalism, and cultural representation evident in prevailing interpretations of classic Heian texts. Renowned for the wealth and sophistication of women’s writing, the literature of the Heian period (794–1192) has long been considered central to the Japanese literary canon and Japanese national identity. Yoda historicizes claims about the inherent femininity of this literature by revisiting key moments in the history of Japanese literary scholarship from the eighteenth century to the present. She argues that by foregrounding women’s voices in Heian literature, the discipline has repeatedly enacted the problematic modernizing gesture in which the “feminine” is recognized, canceled, and then contained within a national framework articulated in masculine terms.Moving back and forth between a critique of modern discourses on Heian literature and close analyses of the Heian texts themselves, Yoda sheds light on some of the most persistent interpretive models underwriting Japanese literary studies, particularly the modern paradigm of a masculine national subject. She proposes new directions for disciplinary critique and suggests that historicized understandings of premodern texts offer significant insights into contemporary feminist theories of subjectivity and agency.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aFeminism and literaturezJapanxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aFeminist literary criticismzJapan. 0aJapanese literaturexWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aJapanese literatureyHeian period, 794-1185xHistory and criticism. 0aWomen and literaturezJapanxHistoryyTo 1500. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / General.2bisacsh1 aChow, Rey, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHarootunian, Harry, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMiyoshi, Masao, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822385875zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822385875423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822385875/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  Duke Univers